reviewText:
The movie was quite slow and overall left me disappointed. I am not a fan of the frenetic, mindless, action and explosions that characterizes most "thrillers" this days, but the pacing of this film was way too slow, and there was not enough dramatic tension, imo, to justify the slow steady march of the plot.
{possible spoiler}
Perhaps most significantly, the anti-climax of an ending was quite a let-down.  Moreover, I would tend to agree with the dour character in the movie who notes that any plan to stop terrorism that includes offering carte-blanche citizenship in a Western Democracy to a man who has spent millions of dollars funding terror is an unacceptable plan. On the one hand, I found myself cheering for the plan to work at the end because I had come to have sympathetic feelings towards Gunther and I wanted to see Abdullah repent and find redemption. Yet, on the other hand, I couldn't get over the fact that Abdullah, up to the end, showed no signs of repentance and that Gunther's plan involved offering Abdullah a clean slate with few caveats. So, after the surprise twist at the end I felt Gunther's frustration and sense of betrayal, but I also could understand why the others had acted as they had, at least towards Abdullah.
